Oyster_Larvae_GBE

Matthew LH. Cheng

10/4/2021

This document details the workflow, figures, and analyses for Stasse et al. 2021 - Temporal Dynamics of Eastern Oyster Larval Abundance in Great Bay Estuary, New Hampshire. This has been submitted and accepted in the Journal of Shellfish Research.

Figure 2. Physicochemical data from 2018, 2019, and 2020. Data include (A) temperature, (B) salinity, and (C) pH.

Figure 3. Crassostrea virgincia D-hinge and veliger larval abundances in (A and B) 2018, (C and D) 2019, and (E and F) 2020. Standard error bars are shown with each data point.

Figure 4. Crassostrea virginica larval counts (A) D-hinge and (B) veliger collected from Great Bay Estuary, NH in 2018, 2019, and 2020. Black circles denote observations of larval counts during a given sampling period. Midlines within each boxplot represent median values, and the hinges indicate the first and third quartile ranges (25th and 75th percentiles).

Figure 5. Back transformed regression model of D-hinge oyster larvae and temperature (°C) with corresponding trendline and 95% confidence intervals shown in gray.

Figure 6. Crassostrea virginica spat settlement m−2 and SE observed in 2020 in Great Bay Estuary (GBE).
